# Define critical columns for analysis
critical_columns = ['obs_value', 'GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)', 
                    'Life expectancy at birth, total (years)', 
                    'Birth rate, crude (per 1,000 people)']

# Drop rows where obs_value is missing
cleaned_df = merged_df.dropna(subset=['obs_value'])

# For specific analysis, drop rows missing the relevant variable
# Example: For GDP analysis
gdp_analysis_df = cleaned_df.dropna(subset=['GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)'])

# Example: For Life Expectancy analysis
life_exp_analysis_df = cleaned_df.dropna(subset=['Life expectancy at birth, total (years)'])

# Optionally, fill less critical numeric columns with median
cleaned_df.fillna({
    'Hospital beds (per 1,000 people)': cleaned_df['Hospital beds (per 1,000 people)'].median(),
    'GDP growth (annual %)': cleaned_df['GDP growth (annual %)'].median()
}, inplace=True)

World Map Chart¶

In [25]:
# Import required libraries
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

#  Load indicator and metadata CSV files
indicator_df = pd.read_csv('Azar_indicator_1.csv')
metadata_df = pd.read_csv('Azar_metadata.csv')

# Get the latest year from indicator_df
latest_year = indicator_df['time_period'].max()

# Filter data for that year only
map_data = indicator_df[indicator_df['time_period'] == latest_year]

# Corrected Merge: Match 'time_period' with 'year'
map_data = pd.merge(
    map_data,
    metadata_df,
    left_on=['country', 'time_period'],
    right_on=['country', 'year'],
    how='left'
)

# Rename alpha_3_code_x to a usable name
map_data = map_data.rename(columns={'alpha_3_code_x': 'alpha_3_code'})

# Load the Natural Earth shapefile (.shp)
world = gpd.read_file('shapefiles/ne_110m_admin_0_countries.shp')

# Merge the GeoDataFrame with your map data using alpha-3 codes
world_data = world.merge(map_data, left_on='SOV_A3', right_on='alpha_3_code')

# Plot the World Map using GeoPandas' native plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 10))

world_data.plot(
    column='obs_value',
    ax=ax,
    legend=True,
    cmap='OrRd',
    edgecolor='black'
)

# Add titles and remove axes
indicator_title = map_data['indicator'].iloc[0]
ax.set_title(f"{indicator_title} by Country ({latest_year})", fontsize=16)
ax.set_axis_off()

# Show the map
plt.show()

The figure shows disparities in postnatal care coverage by country. The data is reported only by a few nations, Mozambique, Yemen, and Afghanistan, with reporting limited to the world or low healthcare outreach. The darker shades represent the percentages of newborns that receive postnatal care within two days of being delivered. The visual portrays the importance of grounding these areas in efforts to provide better services within these underprivileged regions and invigorate data collection mechanisms that are insufficient in the global healthcare sector.

Bar Chart – Top 10 Countries by Indicator Value¶

In [46]:
from plotnine import *

# Sort and get top 10 countries by obs_value
top10 = map_data.sort_values(by='obs_value', ascending=False).head(10)

# Create larger bar plot
(
    ggplot(top10, aes(x='reorder(country, obs_value)', y='obs_value')) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity', fill='skyblue') +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(
        title=f'Top 10 Countries by {top10["indicator"].iloc[0]} ({latest_year})',
        x='Country',
        y='Postnatal Care Coverage (%)'
    ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(
        figure_size=(12, 8),  # Increased width and height
        axis_title=element_text(size=12),
        axis_text=element_text(size=11),
        plot_title=element_text(size=14, weight='bold')
    )
)

The above bar chart shows the top countries with the maximum postnatal care coverage in 2023. The percentage is highest in Mozambique, then Yemen, and Afghanistan. This visualization effectively shows in a way that some of the underdeveloped countries, even with their economic challenges, are doing their best to improve newborn healthcare. However, data scarcity is indicated by the few number of countries, which are reported. This calls for wider involvement of reporters, and as such, needs to be used to monitor progress and manage gaps in global health reporting.

from plotnine import *

# Rename the birth rate column for easier plotting
birth_rate_data = cleaned_df.rename(columns={
    'Birth rate, crude (per 1,000 people)': 'birth_rate'
})

# Drop missing values
birth_rate_data = birth_rate_data.dropna(subset=['birth_rate'])

# Use latest year data
latest_year_birth = birth_rate_data['time_period'].max()
birth_rate_latest = birth_rate_data[birth_rate_data['time_period'] == latest_year_birth]

# Get Top 10 countries by birth rate
top10_birth_rate = birth_rate_latest.sort_values(by='birth_rate', ascending=False).head(10)

# Plot Bar Chart
(
    ggplot(top10_birth_rate, aes(x='reorder(country, birth_rate)', y='birth_rate')) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity', fill='salmon') +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(
        title=f'Top 10 Countries by Birth Rate ({latest_year_birth})',
        x='Country',
        y='Birth Rate (per 1,000 people)'
    ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(
        figure_size=(12, 8),
        axis_title=element_text(size=12),
        axis_text=element_text(size=11),
        plot_title=element_text(size=14, weight='bold')
    )
)

It can be seen in this chart that, in terms of birth rates, countries such as Benin and Tanzania are at the top. Generally, high birth rates correspond with high pressure on the healthcare systems, in particular on maternal and child healthcare systems. Demand for postnatal care in these countries tends to be inherently higher, and the visualization shows regions to strengthen healthcare infrastructure in these nations. In addition, it is a dominant indicator to policymakers for the task of aligning healthcare resources to demographic trends to improve child survival rates in high birth rate countries.

Scatterplot – GDP vs Indicator Value with Regression Line¶

In [32]:
from plotnine import *

# Rename for easier use
scatter_data = cleaned_df.rename(columns={
    'GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)': 'gdp_per_capita'
})

# Scatterplot: Postnatal Care vs GDP per Capita
(
    ggplot(scatter_data, aes(x='gdp_per_capita', y='obs_value')) +
    geom_point(aes(color='time_period'), size=3, alpha=0.7) +
    geom_smooth(method='lm', color='red') +
    scale_color_gradient(low='blue', high='orange') +
    labs(
        title='Postnatal Care vs GDP per Capita',
        subtitle='UNICEF Data Across Countries and Years',
        x='GDP per Capita (constant 2015 USD)',
        y='Postnatal Care Coverage (%)',
        color='Year'
    ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(
        figure_size=(12, 6),
        axis_title=element_text(size=12),
        plot_title=element_text(size=14, weight='bold'),
        plot_subtitle=element_text(size=11)
    )
)

In this scatterplot, there is a positive correlation between GDP per capita and Postnatal care coverage. However, the upward trend reflects that Wealthier countries give better access to children to use in the health care of newborns. However, there are several countries whose GDP is lower but whose postnatal care percentages are also very commendable, which suggests that policy focus can overcome economic limitations. The graph reinforces the economic strength is a role in healthcare outcomes, as well as suggests that targeted health interventions can also help improve child health even in low-income settings.

This visualization shows how special care for early life contributes greatly to checking general health conditions, and this strongly endorses the need for integrated healthcare strategies for sustainable development.

In [40]:
from plotnine import *

# Group by year and calculate average postnatal care coverage
time_series_data = (
    cleaned_df.groupby('time_period')['obs_value']
    .mean()
    .reset_index()
)

# Plot the time-series chart
(
    ggplot(time_series_data, aes(x='time_period', y='obs_value')) +
    geom_line(color='purple', size=1.5) +
    geom_point(color='darkblue', size=3) +
    labs(
        title='Global Average Postnatal Care Coverage Over Time',
        subtitle='Average % of Newborns with Postnatal Health Contact',
        x='Year',
        y='Average Postnatal Care Coverage (%)'
    ) +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks=sorted(time_series_data['time_period'].unique())) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(
        figure_size=(12, 6),
        axis_title=element_text(size=12),
        plot_title=element_text(size=14, weight='bold'),
        plot_subtitle=element_text(size=11)
    )
)

This time series chart displays the global mean number of born receiving postnatal care from 2010 to 2023. There is a clear upward trend of great progress in global health initiatives. It lines up with global crises as an intensified focus on healthcare in the peaks around 2020. Despite that, the fluctuations and decline in 2022 reveal problems in sustaining the continuous provision of health care. The visualization stresses the need to sustain international efforts for continual improvements in maternal and child health services and services.

UNICEF Global Health Indicators Report¶

In this report, UNICEF’s key indicator data from various countries and years is visualized. We combine economic and health indicators to expose who is doing better and who is doing worse across the globe.

Key Themes¶

  • Global Inequality: Constantly high health challenges of children in low income countries.
  • Economic Impact: Improvement is driven by economic growth and so a strong correlation between indicator values and GDP is expected.
  • Time Trends: The global average shows positive progress over recent years.
  • Urgent Attention: Certain nations are still quite far behind and so have to be intervened upon immediately.

About the Data¶

  • Data Source: UNICEF Global Indicators (2024 edition)
  • Indicators Used: It differs by country and year (for example, child mortality and immunization coverage).
  • Additional Context: Merged with World Bank socioeconomic data (GDP, population)
